<dl id="n12009h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12009h">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12009h"> 9(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> casque of telephonist <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12009h"><li>FW 431.03 </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/lexqA.htm#n12009h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/l39qA.htm#n12009h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n12009h">MS BL 47483-112</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:178 <a name="qAd5" href="../../FF/fdra/qda.htm#qAd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/qA/qAd5.htm#n12009h">Draft: III&sect;2A.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[On how a writer needs to be receptive to new sensibilities]</font>: Victor Hugo appelait cela tenir le r&ocirc;le de &lsquo;cristal sonore&rsquo;. M. Mac Orlan pr&eacute;f&egrave;re le terme de &lsquo;Central t&eacute;l&eacute;phonique&rsquo;. Voil&agrave; ce que doit &ecirc;tre l&apos;&eacute;crivain. C&apos;est bien singulier. Quel rapport entre un esprit r&eacute;ceptif et un esprit cr&eacute;ateur? Descartes, dans le silence de son po&ecirc;le, aura donc un r&ocirc;le moins humain, laissera moins de traces dans la vie, qu&apos;<mark>une demoiselle du Bureau central, abasourdie sous son casque</mark>? Et le fran&ccedil;ais traditionnel serait donc inhabile &agrave; traduire la fameuse &ldquo;&acirc;me moderne&rdquo;, qui est, para&icirc;t-il, purement passive, incoh&eacute;rente et enfantine? Voil&agrave; ce que signifie cette image, moderne, elle aussi. La modernit&eacute; exige m&ecirc;me, para&icirc;t-il, que les arts changent de condition. <br><font color="green">[Victor Hugo called this playing the role of &lsquo;sonorous crystal&rsquo;. M. Mac Orlan prefers the term &lsquo;Telephone Centre&rsquo;. That is the role of the writer and it is a strange one. How does the receptive spirit relate to the creative spirit? Descartes, in the silence of his stove, would have a less human role, would leave fewer traces in life, than a young lady in the Central Bureau, stunned beneath her headphones? And the traditional French would then be unable to translate the famous &ldquo;modern soul&rdquo;, which is, it seems, purely passive, incoherent and childlike? This is what that image, modern in itself, really means. Modernity even demands, it seems, that the arts change their condition.]</font> <small> Jacques Boulenger &amp; Andr&eacute; Th&eacute;rive, <a name="SOIR" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SOIR"><cite title="source">Les Soir&eacute;es du Grammaire-Club</cite></a> (1924) 148</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Casque: telephonist&apos;s headphones. </mm> </dd></dl>
